	<div id="gtco-features"  >
		<div class="gtco-container">
		<div class="row">
				<div class="col-md-8 text-justify gtco-heading">
					<h2>Euglena</h2>
					<p>
					
					The members of Euglena are characterized by an elongated cell with one nucleus, numerous chloroplasts a contractile vacuole an eyespot, 
					and one or two flagella. Unlike plant cells, Euglena lack a rigid cellulose wall and have a flexible pellicle that allows them to change shape. 
					Though they are photosynthetic, most species can also feed heterotrophically and absorb food directly through the cell surface via phagocytosis.
					Food is often stored as a specialized complex carbohydrate known as paramylon, which enables the organisms to survive in low-light conditions. 
					The organelle stigma (a light detecting and photo-sensitive eyespot) allows certain light wavelengths to be detected so the Euglena can adjust 
					its position accordingly to enhance photosynthesis. They reproduce asexually by means of longitudinal cell division, and several species produce
					dormant cysts under unfavourable conditions.
					</p>
				</div>
				
					<div class="col-md-4">
					<img src="images/euglena3.jpg" style = "width:100%; height:300px;;">
				</div>
			</div>
					<div class="row">
					<div class="col-md-5" >
					<img src="images/euglena4.jpg" style = "width:100%; height:430px;;">
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-7 text-justify gtco-heading">
					<h2>Habitat and conservation</h2>
					<p >
					
					The members of Euglena usually live in fresh and brackish water habitats such as ponds rich in organic matter and some even in marine waters. 
					They are more commonly found in still ponds, lakes and waters. Some species can form green or red “blooms” in ponds or lakes.
					They are cosmopolitan in distribution. When numerous, they give a greenish colour to the pond water.
					
					</p>
				</div>
				
			</div>
		
	</div>
